{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RJ4Y5jGThNZBKn5e8vTKcv","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→artifact: spec\n     3→loop: 8\n     4→project: ralph-burning-rewrite\n     5→backend: codex(gpt-5.4-xhigh)\n     6→role: planner\n     7→created_at: 2026-03-12T01:04:12Z\n     8→---\n     9→\n    10→I’m reviewing `prompt.md`, completed loop specs, and git checkpoints to determine what is already delivered and what the next missing feature should be. After that I’ll write a spec only for the first unimplemented roadmap slice.\n    11→I have the checkpoint sequence; next I’m narrowing to the planning inputs and current implementation surface so I can tell whether roadmap step 8 is still actually missing or partly landed already.\n    12→The code already contains some stage names and state fields for later roadmap items, so I’m checking whether those are just type scaffolding or actual delivered behavior before choosing the next feature.\n    13→I’m past the roadmap handoff and into the code now. The key question is whether loop 8 is still missing or whether completion-panel/amendment behavior already leaked into loop 7’s implementation, which would push the next feature further down the roadmap.\n    14→Loop 7 is more substantial than the tracker implies: retry, remediation to implementation, pause/resume, and amendment queue accumulation are already in the engine. I’m checking the remaining helpers and tests to see which parts of roadmap step 8 are still absent rather than already delivered.\n    15→The current engine already executes through `completion_panel`, `acceptance_qa`, and `final_review`, but it appears to treat them with generic validation semantics. I’m verifying whether any feature-specific completion-round logic, final-review gating, or amendment-queue processing is actually implemented, because that decides whether the next spec is loop 8 hardening or the next preset family.\n    16→I’ve confirmed loop 7 from the actual diff: it added exactly the retry/resume/remediation slice. What remains around step 8 is not “run the later stages” but “give those later stages their own state machine”: completion rounds, amendment-queue lifecycle, and completion/final-review semantics are still generic or stubbed.\n    17→I need one more pass through the legacy reference artifacts, because the roadmap only names step 8 while the current rewrite already has generic versions of those stages. I’m using the old specs only to recover the intended semantics for completion rounds and amendment handling, not to plan around legacy storage or protocol.\n    18→# Feature: Completion Rounds, Late-Stage Acceptance, and Durable Amendments\n    19→\n    20→## Description\n    21→Approved loop artifacts `001` through `007` and checkpoint history through `4b10f4e` show the rewrite has completed the roadmap through retry, remediation, pause/resume, and failure-class handling. The next missing slice is roadmap step 8. The current standard-flow engine already executes `completion_panel`, `acceptance_qa`, and `final_review`, but it still treats them as generic validation stages: `completion_rounds` never advances beyond `1`, `StageCursor::advance_completion_round` and `JournalEventType::CompletionRoundAdvanced` are unused, `AmendmentQueued` and `processed_count` are unused, `projects/<id>/amendments/` is only scaffolding, and a run can currently complete while `amendment_queue.pending` is non-empty. This feature should add the real late-stage state machine for the standard preset: completion-round advancement, durable amendment queue persistence/application, and stage-specific continue-vs-complete behavior for `completion_panel`, `acceptance_qa`, and `final_review`, without re-implementing loops 1-7 or enabling non-standard flows yet.\n    22→\n    23→## Acceptance Criteria\n    24→- [ ] Loop-7 behavior remains unchanged for `qa` and `review`: their `RequestChanges` remediation path still advances work cycles directly back to `implementation`, and the new logic applies only to `completion_panel`, `acceptance_qa`, and `final_review`.\n    25→- [ ] Late-stage transition rules are explicit and stage-specific: `completion_panel` `Approved` advances to `acceptance_qa`; `acceptance_qa` `Approved` advances to `final_review` when the flow definition enables final review and otherwise completes the run; `final_review` `Approved` completes the run; `Rejected` at any late stage fails the run terminally with `QaReviewOutcomeFailure`.\n    26→- [ ] `ConditionallyApproved` or `RequestChanges` at any late stage does not silently proceed and does not terminally fail; after the late-stage payload/artifact pair is durably committed, the engine queues every `follow_up_or_amendments` item as a durable amendment, emits `amendment_queued` journal events, emits one `completion_round_advanced` journal event, and moves the cursor to `planning` for the next completion round.\n    27→- [ ] On a `completion_round_advanced` transition, `StageCursor.completion_round` increments, `attempt` resets to `1`, the next stage becomes `planning`, and `cycle` stays unchanged at that boundary. `run.json.completion_rounds` tracks the highest round reached and remains monotonic independently of `cycle_history`.\n    28→- [ ] When the next completion round successfully leaves `planning` and re-enters `implementation`, the engine emits `cycle_advanced`, increments the work-cycle number, and records the new cycle in `cycle_history`. Completion-round continuation must therefore advance completion round first and work cycle only when new implementation work actually begins.\n    29→- [ ] Queued amendments are persisted under `projects/<id>/amendments/` using atomic writes and a typed canonical record that includes at least amendment id, source stage, source cycle, source completion round, body, and created timestamp. `run.json` stores the same queue in structured form; raw `serde_json::Value` placeholders are no longer the canonical queue model in this slice.\n    30→- [ ] Pending queued amendments are injected into the next `planning` invocation in deterministic order. They are marked processed and removed from pending on-disk state only after the `planning` stage commit succeeds; planning invocation failure or planning commit failure must leave them pending and reusable on `run resume`.\n    31→- [ ] `JournalEventType::CompletionRoundAdvanced` and `JournalEventType::AmendmentQueued` have concrete builders and are emitted in canonical order after the source late-stage commit. Public `run history`/`run tail` output includes those events without ever treating amendment files or runtime logs as durable history artifacts.\n    32→- [ ] `run_completed` may be persisted only when both the structured amendment queue and the `amendments/` directory contain no pending items. A late-stage conditional approval must never allow a completed snapshot with leftover queued amendments.\n    33→- [ ] `run resume` reconstructs pending amendments and the current completion round from canonical state and resumes from the first incomplete durable stage without duplicating already-processed amendments or losing queued ones.\n    34→- [ ] Failure invariant: if amendment persistence fails before any `amendment_queued` event is committed, no queue entry becomes visible in `run.json` and no `completion_round_advanced` event is written.\n    35→- [ ] Failure invariant: if some amendment files and `amendment_queued` events are durable but snapshot or cursor advancement fails afterward, those amendments remain pending and discoverable for resume; the run must end in a non-completed state with `active_run == null`.\n    36→- [ ] Failure invariant: if completion is otherwise ready but pending amendments are detected during terminalization, completion is blocked and the run remains resumable; that guard must not delete, drain, or silently mark any pending amendment as processed.\n    37→- [ ] Conformance and unit coverage are added for: completion-panel-driven continuation into round 2, acceptance-QA-driven continuation, final-review-driven continuation, terminal rejection at late stages, successful completion after a second round, resume with pending late-stage amendments, and the completion guard that blocks success while amendments remain queued.\n    38→- [ ] `quick_dev`, `docs_change`, and `ci_improvement` remain unsupported in `run start` after this slice; this feature hardens only the standard-flow late-stage semantics.\n    39→\n    40→## Files to Modify/Create\n    41→- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs` - add late-stage transition table, completion-round advancement, planning restart, amendment injection/drain, and completion guard\n    42→- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workflow_composition/mod.rs` - route acceptance/final-review behavior through flow-definition metadata instead of generic hard-coded assumptions\n    43→- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/shared/domain.rs` - make cursor round/cycle transitions explicit for late-stage restart boundaries\n    44→- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/model.rs` - add typed queued-amendment records and finalize journal event enum usage for completion-round/amendment events\n    45→- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/journal.rs` - add builders for `completion_round_advanced` and `amendment_queued`\n    46→- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/service.rs` - add ports/use-cases for reading, writing, draining, and reconciling durable amendment queue state\n    47→- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/adapters/fs.rs` - implement filesystem-backed amendment queue persistence under `projects/<id>/amendments/`\n    48→- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/shared/error.rs` - add explicit amendment-queue and completion-guard error variants\n    49→- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/workflow_engine_test.rs` - cover completion-round restarts, queue drain/apply behavior, and late-stage failure invariants\n    50→- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/journal_test.rs` - cover new journal event builders and ordering expectations\n    51→- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/adapter_contract_test.rs` - cover atomic amendment queue persistence and non-lossy failure behavior\n    52→- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/cli.rs` - extend CLI-level assertions for round advancement, resume, and blocked completion\n    53→- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/run_completion_rounds.feature` - add public scenarios for completion rounds, late-stage amendments, and blocked completion\n    54→\n    55→## Dependencies\n    56→- Requires: Loop 7 (Retry, Remediation, Resume, and Failure Class Semantics)\n    57→- Blocks: Non-standard preset execution on the shared engine (`quick_dev`, `docs_change`, `ci_improvement`)\n    58→\n    59→---\n    60→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01SkHWtcfo821tZDM1uBq1La","session_id":"22e84bba-de3d-49c0-8e45-9206d1dfe4ad","uuid":"02b7f3e5-4989-4cf7-bcc1-dbf120e700ec"}
